  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3391201026" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3391201026" />
    <a title="Sofia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia"><img alt="Sofia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607792875p2/114413220.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3391201026?book_show_action=true">Feb 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sofia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sofia" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia">Sofia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=disappointments">disappointments</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=gary-stu">gary-stu</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=multiple-perspectives">multiple-perspectives</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=problematic">problematic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=that-one-character-i-hate">that-one-character-i-hate</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=idek-anymore-guys">idek-anymore-guys</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=le-sigh">le-sigh</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=school-drama">school-drama</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=stock-side-characters">stock-side-characters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=what-a-terrible-ending">what-a-terrible-ending</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3391201026" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3250795911982617583">Surprise, surprise. <br/>I hated it. <br/><br/><br/>Even if I ignore or push aside the clearly problematic elements of this book, the characters are cliche and the mystery is predictable, making this a very mediocre novel indeed. <br/><br/><br/><i>One of Us Is Lying</i> follows four teenagers who watched their classmate Simon die in front of their eyes due to an allergic reaction. Addy, the princess. Nate, the bad boy. Bronwyn, the nerd. Cooper, the jock. Four teen drama stereotypes in one room. One dead person. And one mystery. <br/><br/>Most of</span>
  <span id="freeText3250795911982617583" style="display:none">Surprise, surprise. <br />I hated it. <br /><br /><br />Even if I ignore or push aside the clearly problematic elements of this book, the characters are cliche and the mystery is predictable, making this a very mediocre novel indeed. <br /><br /><br /><i>One of Us Is Lying</i> follows four teenagers who watched their classmate Simon die in front of their eyes due to an allergic reaction. Addy, the princess. Nate, the bad boy. Bronwyn, the nerd. Cooper, the jock. Four teen drama stereotypes in one room. One dead person. And one mystery. <br /><br />Most of my review will include spoilers, which are boxed off by siren emojis (🚨). That's because most of the problematic content is a spoiler for the big plot twist (which wasn't big at all, because I predicted it from the start, but that's also a spoiler, so stay tuned). <br /><br /><br />Like I said earlier, even if I ignore the abysmal problematic aspects, there's nothing in this book that's objectively good, either. The mystery is literally just about who put peanut oil in Simon's cup. That's just not enough to hold my interest. I don't care about Simon because he's a jerk. I don't care about the mystery because it's not fascinating or intriguing. I don't care about the characters because they're trash. <br /><br /><br />Speaking of the characters, they were all stereotypes. I can kind of see where McManus is coming from--I believe she was trying to twist the stereotypes to show that everyone can be hiding something--but the plot twists she used were cliche and uninteresting and utterly, utterly predictable. In other words, she failed. They were just dull. Their character development relied solely on our prior knowledge of these tropes. Also, the nerd-meets-bad-boy-and-changes-him-for-the-better trope is so grossly overused. <br /><br />I half expected Bronwyn to whip off her glasses and suddenly become beautiful or something. There was actually a scene where Bronwyn put her hair down and everyone was like "ahhh you're so pretty with your hair down."<br /><br />I have seen this before.<br />I am not impressed.<br /><br /><br />This book is told from four points of view, one per main character, and they were indistinguishable. They all sounded exactly the same. And <b>they were all written in first person, which made the mystery even less interesting, because there wasn't really a mystery with these people. </b>More to come in the spoilers. All the problems these characters dealt with were very shallow, surface-level, and typical. <br /><br />Throwback to that scene where Addy cut her hair to show how little she needed her boyfriend after their break-up.<br />Do I look like I care? <br />She's attempting to be tough and a strong female character and she falls flat on her perfect face. <br /><br /><br /><br />🚨🚨🚨<b>SPOILERS AHEAD</b>🚨🚨🚨<br /><br /><br /><br />This is where I showcase my main problems with this book. <br /><br />First of all, the plot twist? I predicted it from the start. It was blatantly obvious that Addy, Bronwyn, Cooper, and Nate had nothing to do with this murder. There was some suspicious stuff going on with some of the characters, but it was just thrown in there to make it seem like a mystery. But something didn't add up. <b>There was no physical, possible way for any of the four characters to have killed Simon. </b>It was clear from the very first scene, when he died. So, so bland, predictable, and obvious. <br /><br /><br />Second of all, WHAT WAS THAT PLOT TWIST.<br />I'M SO MAD.<br /><i>I CAN'T EVEN PROPERLY EXPRESS HOW MUCH RAGE I HAVE INSIDE ME. </i><br /><br /><br />Simon kills himself.<br />That's the big plot twist.<br />He killed himself with peanut oil.<br /><br /><b>What really got me was the absolutely terrible, despicable representation of mental health. </b><br />Here's some backstory. Simon was the creator of this gossip site that spreads awful information about his classmates and has led people to attempt suicide. <br />Later on in the book, it is revealed that Simon himself had depression. He frequented these terrible websites that encourage school shootings and he said some things about how he wanted to go down creatively, bringing everyone with him for revenge. <br /><br />So he committed suicide and framed his classmates. <br /><br />I don't have a problem with having a maniac as the victim, but <b>I do have a problem with blaming his insane behavior on his mental illness. </b>The message this spreads is that all depressed people want to commit suicide just to get revenge on the world. Which is just so, so wrong. <br /><br />And then he was villainized BECAUSE of his depression. Obviously Simon is a villain because he's just a terrible person, but what we shouldn't do is make him the bad guy just because of his mental illness. There was also a side character who was depressed and ended up being another villain.<br /><br />I'm so tired.<br /><br />And finally, suicide is not a fun little mystery for your high schoolers to "solve." Using it as a plot twist is potentially triggering and also very harmful. The rep was absolutely terrible and there's no excusing how bad it was.<br /><br /><br />Also, can we stop using sexuality like it's some amazing, scandalous plot twist? Because it's not. <br /><br /><br />And, to top it all off, we have this so-called <i>drama</i> going on between Nate and Bronwyn at the end, where Nate essentially dumps Bronwyn for no reason other than <b>"I'm not good enough for you and you don't deserve me."</b> A), why do you get to decide that for her? B), this is so oversaturated and I'm extremely tired of it all. <br /><br /><br /><br />🚨🚨🚨<b>SPOILERS HAVE ENDED</b>🚨🚨🚨<br /><br /><br /><br />In conclusion, I recommend this to no one. The mystery was terrible, the characters were cardboard cut-outs, I wanted the romance to rot in a deep hole, and the portrayal of mental illness was problematic.<br /><br /><br />0.1 stars; I can't believe trees DIED for this book to be printed</span>
  <a data-text-id="3250795911982617583" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


